<font color="#FF0000">SEMINAR: 1ST CLASS MEETING</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 10 21:31:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Our seminar met for the first time last night; we were a mix of 35 students, veterans, visiting faculty, friends, and guests. We spent the first hour reviewing course objectives and seminar-related activities; the need to manage time; how to get started; and class expectations. <br><br>
The second hour Professor E. Schroeder and I cued-up and showed selected film clips to differentiate Hollywood's view of Viet Nam, and we contrasted these views with clips of actual combat footage. Students and veterans were encouraged to speak out, comment, and consider the clips from their individual perspectives. The veterans, both U.S. and ARVAN, interacted well with the students and provided a broad range of both insightful as well as humerous commentary to selected scenes from: The Deer Hunter, Apocyplyse Now, Full Metal Jacket, followed by combat film shot during the Tet Offensive. Comments and discussion stimulated a broad range of exchanges that brought the students, veterans, and visitors together. We ended the 2nd hour with the classic &quot;sunset&quot; scene from Green Berets. While the veterans smiled, none and waited for the students to comment.... none of the students immediately picked-up on the curiosity of an ocean &quot;sunset&quot; in Viet Nam. Then it hit everybody and there were smiles all around.<br><br>
The seminar setting allowed a relaxed atmosphere for all... students, veterans, and guests. The general feeling was that we are off to a great beginning.<br><br>
All attending the class received hard-copy of the course-related materials (readings; bibliographies; objectives; and other information. <br><br>
We announced the construction of our new web-site and encouraged the students to visit the PBS/POV site daily.  Class-related materials, a variety of web-links, as well as graphics are available through our new seminar web-site address located at: <br><br>
http://www-honors.ucdavis.edu/html/vietnam/vntp.html<br><br>
You can enter and browse the site now; please note that several components of the site are still under construction. We hope to have everything completed within 10 days.<br><br>
Ultimately, there will be a box for comments and suggestions at the bottom of the site.<br><br>
Please check us out. <br><br>
We ask for your suggestions and recommendations how to improve our web-site lay-out and course-related materials.<br><br>
Regards to all.....<br><br>

